Find all solutions to the equation below:

\[2 (x+{9})^2+16~=~114\]

\[2 (x+{9})^2+16~=~114\]

First, subtract 16 from both sides.

\[2 (x+{9})^2~=~98\]

Second, divide both sides by 2.

\[(x+{9})^2~=~49\]

Undo the squaring. Remember the plus-minus symbol!

\[x+{9}~=~\pm7\]

Subtract 9 from both sides.

\[x~=~-9\pm7\]

So the two solutions are \(x=-2\) and \(x=-16\).

By completing the square, find both solutions to the given equation:

\[x^2-6x~=~40\]

The given equation:

\[x^2-6x~=~40\]

In order to make the left side of the equation a perfect square, we can add \(\left(\frac{-6}{2}\right)^2=9\) to both sides (where -6 is the linear coefficient).

\[x^2-6x+9~=~40+9\]

\[x^2-6x+9~=~49\]

We can rewrite the left side in factored form. Notice that because the left side is a perfect square, we get a squared binomial.

\[(x-3)^2~=~49\]

Because the squaring function is not one-to-one, when we "undo" it in algebra, we need to consider the possibility of multiple solutions. In this case both 7 and -7 produce 49 when squared.

\[x-3~=~\pm 7\]

And, lastly, subtract -3 from both sides of the equation.

\[x~=~3\pm7\]

\[x~=~10~~~~~~~~\text{or}~~~~~~~~x~=~-4\]

\[x^2-8x+16~=~16\]

\[x^2-8x+16~=~16\]

We can rewrite the left side in factored form. Notice that because the left side is a perfect square, we get a squared binomial.

\[(x-4)^2~=~16\]

Because the squaring function is not one-to-one, when we "undo" it in algebra, we need to consider the possibility of multiple solutions. In this case both 4 and -4 produce 16 when squared.

\[x-4~=~\pm 4\]

And, lastly, subtract -4 from both sides of the equation.

\[x~=~4\pm4\]

Quadratic polynomial \(p\) is defined below in standard form. \[p(x)~=~{3}x^{2}+{48}x+{183}\]

By completing the square, you can rewrite the quadratic polynomial in vertex form:

\[p(x) = a(x-h)^2+k\]

where \((h,k)\) is the vertex of the parabola. Determine the coordinates of the vertex of quadratic polynomial \(p\).

  • \(h=\)
  • \(k=\)

We are given \(p(x)~=~{3}x^{2}+{48}x+{183}\). From the first two terms, factor out 3.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(x^{2}+{16}x\right)+{183}\]

Determine the constant needed to complete the square (of the expression inside parentheses) by dividing the linear coefficient by 2 and then squaring the result. \(\left(\frac{16}{2}\right)^2 ~=~ \left(8\right)^2 ~=~ 64\). Add and subtract this amount inside the parentheses.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(x^{2}+{16}x+{64}-{64}\right)+{183}\]

Notice the first three terms inside the parentheses are a perfect square. Rewrite them in factored form.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(\left(x+{8}\right)^2-64\right)+{183}\]

Distribute the 3.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(x+{8}\right)^2-192+{183}\]

Combine the constants.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(x+{8}\right)^2 -{9}\]

And so:

\[h = -8\] \[k = -9\]

We are given \(p(x)~=~{3}x^{2}+{36}x+{115}\). From the first two terms, factor out 3.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(x^{2}+{12}x\right)+{115}\]

Determine the constant needed to complete the square (of the expression inside parentheses) by dividing the linear coefficient by 2 and then squaring the result. \(\left(\frac{12}{2}\right)^2 ~=~ \left(6\right)^2 ~=~ 36\). Add and subtract this amount inside the parentheses.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(x^{2}+{12}x+{36}-{36}\right)+{115}\]

Notice the first three terms inside the parentheses are a perfect square. Rewrite them in factored form.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(\left(x+{6}\right)^2-36\right)+{115}\]

Distribute the 3.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(x+{6}\right)^2-108+{115}\]

Combine the constants.

\[p(x)~=~3\left(x+{6}\right)^2 +{7}\]

And so:

\[h = -6\] \[k = 7\]
